  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and frameworks aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Sets global standards for combating money laundering\n- 40 recommendations that most countries have adopted\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides guidelines for international cooperation\n- Encourages member states to criminalize money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision guidelines\n- Establishes banking sector standards for anti-money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) regulations\n- Provides oversight and recommendations for financial systems\n\n5. Individual country laws\n- Most nations have domestic laws implementing international standards\n- Examples include the U.S. Bank Secrecy Act and EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nWhile there's no single universal law, these frameworks create a comprehensive global approach to preventing money laundering.",
